sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER INNINGS WIN.
West Indies international Phil Simmons scored a four-wicket haul of 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by one wicket and 39 runs over two days to take the county championship lead.

Their stay at the top may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After Somerset had been bowled out for 83 at Grace Road on the opening day, Leicestershire extended their first innings lead to 94 runs before being bowled out for 296, with England international Andy Caddick scoring three for 83.
Somerset, who were 213 down, started their second innings strongly before Simmons stepped in and knocked them out with 174.
Essex, however, look confident of regaining top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them firm control of their game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, hit 158, his first century of the championship, as Essex scored 372 and took an 82-run lead in the first innings.
By the end, Yorkshire's lead had grown to 37 runs but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them five for 119 and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, the second man dropped by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed up a four-wicket haul of 45 on Thursday with 80 in Friday's game against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who scored 70 as Surrey finished with 429 points for 234.
Derbyshire resumed their chase for their first championship since 1936, reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody scored six of his 82 points, while Chris Adams (123) and Tim O'Gorman (109) led Derbyshire to 471 and 233 points respectively.
After the disappointment of the weather affecting their opening day of play badly, Kent upped the momentum to down Nottinghamshire by 214 points.
They were held back by Paul Johnson's 84, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague made four for 55.
By Stumps, Kent had reached 108 points from three.

Alan Shearer, the world's most expensive footballer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for a fee of £15 million ($23.4 million), will replace Tony Adams and former captain David Platt, who led the team to the European Championship in June.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer will take up the captaincy on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not make the job his own.
"I'm sure there won't be any problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan he was ready and really wanted to do it.
"It's very difficult to draw a 100 percent conclusion on something like this in four days....
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team's situation, even though he's playing up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 strike partner Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED UP AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat, ending Rotor's short-lived lead.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor will play against Lada Togliatti on 3 September in front of empty stands.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor are in a good position in the championship with 11 games in hand.
Three points behind Alania and two behind Moscow Dynamo, Volgograd remain one game ahead of the leaders and two ahead of the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMA ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Stone Hands" Duran climbs into the ring on Saturday in another bid to maintain his long career.
The 45-year-old Duran will take on 30-year-old unknown Mexican Ariel Cruz in Panama City in a super middleweight non-championship match.
The event, Duran's first in his home country in 10 years, is here called "The Return of the Legend" and Duran still speaks as if he were in his prime.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer admit that the man who has won championships in four different weight categories - lightweight, light-middleweight, middleweight and middleweight - is coming to the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's greatest boxers," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panamanian Boxing Federation.
Duran, whose record of 97-12 stretches back three decades, will be hoping that victory in the 10-man match will give him revenge against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho won a controversial points decision against a Panamanian in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN SPRING DUEL UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky at the US Open.
The 11th-seeded Washington failed to repeat his Wimbledon miracle when he lost 6-3 6-4 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 to hot wildcard Alex O'Brien in a two-hour and 51-minute battle on the stadium court.
Next door, in the stands, 10th-seeded Rios lost to another Wimbledon player - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The spirited left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's schedule ran smoothly, although sixth-ranked former champion Agassi had to claw his way out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit, winning 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the evening belonged to the rising stars.
Washington, who came back from a 5-1 deficit in the Wimbledon semi-final against Todd Martin and a two-set deficit in the third set, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won her first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the third set 5-4 before Washington came back.
"I just told myself to give myself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen," said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is in 65th place.
"I maintained my self-control and was proud of myself - normally I would have packed up the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former US collegiate national champion, scored 17 aces to finally defeat the never-dead Washington.
The fifth set stayed on the line until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a service winner down the line, tied the match on the backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold the edge at 5:2 and then converted her eighth match point of the match when Washington found the back of the net for a 40-0 lead.
"You just keep fighting and trying to get him to play a bit.
I think he got a little tight at a couple of points," Washington said. "
But I think he served pretty well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose Wimbledon stampede two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued with the callers and taunted fans in his two-hour and 24-minute live tango with Rios in the stands.
To cheers of joy, Chile supported the confused Chilean and rebuked the tall American who was eating up all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well today, very focused. "
The match turned into a third set tiebreak, which the American won 7-5, much to the disappointment of the spectators.
"I love people when they boo me every day.
It gives me momentum, makes me play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I was playing my best tennis in college when fraternities were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's matzo.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's it.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
I lost too many points, which I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see the day.
I play American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel well on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then shook his body in mock salute to the Rios fans.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they are cheering me on.
After the win, I thought I could give them a bit of a treat. "
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading rusher as a fullback and one of the most athletic players ever to play in central defence, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards in 677 games.
"I want to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans of Philadelphia who have supported me throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to Philadelphia and NFL fans alike. "
Selected as a second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham passed for 1,874-3,362 passing yards (55.7 percent) 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham is already a contracted broadcaster.
